\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ManyangaTremblaySESDiets2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 In a broad survey across low and middle-income economies, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MayenSESDDlowmidIncomeCountries2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 also find that with the exception of fruits in diet, the residents of urban
 areas - particularly with higher SES - have more calorie intakes as well
 as consumption of protein, fats and vitamins relative to starchy items.
 The exploration of variation in quality in the current chapter is aimed
 at addressing many such concerns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some empirical studies also find a relevance of the availability of amenities
 such as clean water on dietary diversity (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MekuriaWubnehDDFactorsEthiopia2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 A control for amenities such as electricity are also used - other than
 total expenditure as our main explanatory variable - in the current chapter
 to examine the variation in food quality across Tanzania.
 In its particular context, rapid urbanisation seems to have brought challenges
 to food security for the lower-income households in the towns and cities
 within Tanzania - even though the country has managed to maintain a broad
 self-sufficiency in basic food items (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "WenbanTNZFoodSecurityUrbanisation2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ).
 The agricultural policy has also focused on a transition from subsistence
