It is common for the empirical studies in sub-Saharan Africa to use the
 income data only indirectly.
 There are two mains reasons for this.
 First, the income-data is much more sparse than for occupation or education
 (only about a quarter of households, for example, have income data available
 in the LSMS survey for Tanzania).
 Second, the predominance of informal sectors further subjects the income
 data to significant measurement errors.
