\begin_layout Standard
The second question examines if an increase in status consumption could
 result in more or less accumulations for the consumers.
 The debates on the relationship between inequality and growth in the literature
 have been divisive.
 The conventional wisdom has relied on the early works from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KuznetsEconomicGrowthIneq2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 who had argued that inequality rises in a country's early (agrarian) stages
 of economic development before declining as its economy matures (industrialises
).
 However, later empirical works have argued for both positive and negative
 effects of inequality on long-term economic growth.
 Those who argue for a positive effect of inequality on growth often emphasise
 how inequality helps innovation (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FoellmiZweimullerIncomedistribInnovations2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) and supports high-return projects (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RosenzweigBinswangerWealtRiskProfitability1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The negative effect of inequality on growth has been argued through unfavourabl
e fiscal policies (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PerottiGrowthIncomeDis1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), political instability (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BenabouInequalityGrowth1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) or decline in human capital (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GalorZeiraIncomeDistrMacro1993,BergOstryInequalityGrowthPanel2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Unless a particular mechanism of growth is inspected, an omitted variable
 bias is likely in such international comparisons as well (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ForbesReassessmentInequalityGrowth2000,BanerjeeDufloInequalityGrowth2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 More importantly, one must also consider the time-period over which growth
 is measured (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HalterInequalityGrowthTime2014,BanerjeeDufloInequalityGrowth2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 As 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HalterInequalityGrowthTime2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 elucidate, the positive effects of inequality tend to be short-term while
 the negative effects are often long-term.
 More recent empirical approaches have highlighted the role of inequality
 in opportunity towards growth in the economy (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "AiyarInequalityOpportunity,BradburyTriestInequalityofOpportunityAggEconPerf2016,MarreroRodriguezInequalityOpportunityVsEffort2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Interpreted as non-necessary consumption, status consumption has also been
 explored as a mechanism that could affect growth.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KnellInequalityStatusGrowth1999"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, for example, delineate how status competitions may lead to a negative
 effect on growth in the developed economies.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CorneoStatusGrowth2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 have also shown a negative effect of status competitions on growth while
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HopkinsStatusInequalityGrowth2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 have highlighted that the positive effect of inequality on growth hinges
 on how the society treats its lowest individuals.
 The proposed model in the current chapter focuses only on the accumulations
 for the consumers rather the the growth in the economy and finds that the
 total consumer accumulations (for the poor as well as the rich) decline
 in an economy if economic inequality rises while all consumers participating
 in status competitions.
\end_layout

