\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}^{*}+\bar{\nu}_{2}^{*}\le\xi$
\end_inset

 translates into the following upper bound for 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega>\lambda$
\end_inset

 (in a growing economy), it is thus evident that an increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 decreases this bound on 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
\bar{\nu}_{1}=G(\lambda,\underline{\lambda},\text{\ensuremath{\omega},\ensuremath{\underline{\omega}}},y_{1},y_{2})\le\frac{\omega/\lambda\underbar{\ensuremath{\omega}}-(\xi-\underbar{\ensuremath{\lambda}})}{\omega/\lambda-1}
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proceeding with first-order conditions under this constraint, the Lagrangian
 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\mathscr{U}+\mu(\frac{\lambda\xi-\omega\underbar{\ensuremath{\omega}}-\underbar{\ensuremath{\lambda}\lambda}}{\lambda-\omega}-G(\lambda,\underline{\lambda},\text{\ensuremath{\omega},\ensuremath{\underline{\omega}}},y_{1},\Delta))$
\end_inset

 leads to the following (Kuhn-Tucker) conditions for an interior solution
 (notice that all constraints being linear ensures that the following first-orde
r-conditions is a necessary condition for local-minima - see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "takayamaanalyticalmethods1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ) where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is the Lagrangian multiplier for the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}^{*}+\bar{\nu}_{2}^{*}\le\xi$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial L}{\partial\underline{\lambda}} & =\frac{\partial L}{\partial\ensuremath{\underline{\omega}}}=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu(\frac{\lambda\xi-\omega\underbar{\ensuremath{\omega}}-\underbar{\ensuremath{\lambda}\lambda}}{\lambda-\omega}-G(\lambda,\underline{\lambda},\text{\ensuremath{\omega},\ensuremath{\underline{\omega}}},y_{1},y_{2})) & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two cases therefore arise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Case I: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\lambda\xi-\omega\underbar{\ensuremath{\omega}}-\underbar{\ensuremath{\lambda}\lambda}}{\lambda-\omega}=G(\lambda,\underline{\lambda},\text{\ensuremath{\omega},\ensuremath{\underline{\omega}}},y_{1},y_{2})$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}^{*}+\bar{\nu}_{2}^{*}=\xi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Case II: 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}^{*}+\bar{\nu}_{2}^{*}<\xi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\mathscr{U}}{\partial\underline{\lambda}}=0$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the unconstrained maximum for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{U}$
\end_inset

 after 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\omega}$
\end_inset

 is eliminated using the population stability condition (see below for details).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Case I, the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}+\bar{\nu}_{2}=\xi$
\end_inset

 (with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\ne0$
\end_inset

 ) directly leads to a solution dependent on 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
\bar{\nu}_{1}=G(\lambda,\underline{\lambda},\text{\ensuremath{\omega},\ensuremath{\underline{\omega}}},y_{1},y_{2})=\frac{\lambda\xi-\omega\underbar{\ensuremath{\omega}}-\underbar{\ensuremath{\lambda}\lambda}}{\lambda-\omega}
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial G}{\partial\xi} & =\frac{1}{1-\frac{\omega}{\lambda}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As long as 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega>\lambda$
\end_inset

, an increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 would decrease 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and a decrease in 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 would increase 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Finiteness constraints on 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}^{*}+\bar{\nu}_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

 therefore suppress the status investments for the poorer consumer.
 Further, as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 is an increasing function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 increasing income difference between the two consumers always increases
 the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega>\lambda$
\end_inset

 would mean that an increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 would decrease 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and a decrease in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 would increase 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
\frac{\partial G}{\partial\Delta}=\frac{1}{1-\frac{\omega}{\lambda}}\frac{\partial\xi}{\partial\Delta}
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results for Case II i.e.
 of local-maximisation of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},u_{2}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 is high enough are less straightforward since both 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},u_{2}$
\end_inset

 depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\nu),\psi(\nu)$
\end_inset

 - whose specific forms have not been yet assumed in the solution.
 Considering a specific form for 
\begin_inset Formula $u(A)=\Gamma\cdot A^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and the population stability condition (see Appendix III), the three unknowns
 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\omega},\underline{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}$
\end_inset

 (with fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda,\omega$
\end_inset

 ) can be solved using the conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial u_{1}}{\partial\bar{\nu}_{1}}=0$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial u_{2}}{\partial\bar{\nu}_{1}}=0$
\end_inset

 and the optimisation of the combined utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{U}$
\end_inset

 (see Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:combined_utility"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 So long as the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{U}$
\end_inset

 ensures that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as a concave function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\omega}$
\end_inset

, we can ascertain that a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\omega}$
\end_inset

 would maximise the combined utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{U}$
\end_inset

.
 Such a solution depends however on the particular form of combined utility
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{U}$
\end_inset

.
 The form of a particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{U}$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 the Pareto concern of how the asset utilities from poor and richer consumer
 are combined in a society thus form an important caveat for the effect
 of income differences on consumer selections 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 A simple setting of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{U}(u_{1},u_{2})=\beta u_{1}+(1-\beta)u_{2}$
\end_inset

 where both consumers are better off with more assets (higher utilities
 from assets) - that we explore numerically in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Numerical-Optimisation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 - does not guarantee that the consumers would decrease status investments
 with lowering of income differences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that there are two factors in the cooperative solution with population
 stability that balance the increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{2}$
\end_inset

 in the long-run.
 First is that the poorer consumer eventually runs out of budget 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 if the 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a lot higher (i.e.
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 is very high) and exercises 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 instead.
 Second is that the richer consumer withdraws with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{2}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 if the poorer consumer gets the promotion to a higher band very easily.
 Both of these both factors - are a result of the population stability condition
 and are thus independent of the combined utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{U}$
\end_inset

.
 As these factors would continue to hold for a non-cooperative solution,
 we can argue that the above dynamics for the effect of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{2}$
\end_inset

 in the long-run remain unchanged for a non-cooperative solution as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, the goal of using the two conditions is to explore the effects
 of income difference 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 on status competitions while incorporating the changes in competitions
 that occur to rise or fall in income-differences in the long-term.
 With the parameters controlling a specific form of 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu),L(\nu)$
\end_inset

 endogenised within the equilibrium conditions, we are able to remedy the
 earlier issue with the short-term equilibrium that changes in income also
 change the competitions and 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu),L(\nu)$
\end_inset

 themselves.
 Unlike with the short-term equilibrium, in other words, the changes in
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta y=y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 correspond to a different 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

 characterised by 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\omega}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 As we show with numerical methods, this relationship does not necessarily
 result in consumers always increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{2}$
\end_inset

 in response to rise in income differences.
\end_layout

